{"id":"2208.08633","submitter":"Alan Stoneham","authors":"Alan Stoneham","title":"Constructing Well-bounded Operators not of type (B) on a Class of\n  Inductive Limits","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Well-bounded operators are linear operators on a Banach space $X$ that have\nan $AC[a,b]$ functional calculus for some interval $[a,b]$. A well-bounded\noperator is of type (B) if it can be written as an integral against a spectral\nfamily of projections, and this is always the case when $X$ is reflexive. There\nare many examples of well-bounded operators on non-reflexive spaces that are\nnot of type (B), and it is open whether there is a non-reflexive Banach space\nupon which every well-bounded operator is of type (B). The spaces constructed\nby Pisier, which answered a conjecture of Grothendieck in the negative, have\nbeen suggested by Cheng and Doust as a candidate to answer this open problem.\nIn this paper, it will be shown that on a class of Banach spaces containing\nthese spaces, there is always a well-bounded operator not of type (B).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 18 Aug 2022 04:52:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-19"}
